pullRequest.body:
We show that the sum defining an Eisenstein Series converges locally uniformly. This is the basis for later proving that they are holomorphic (see #11013 ) and bounded at infinity (see #12456), which combine to show they are modular forms (see #12604).

Several comments on this.

- I think it is more readable (and more robust) to write `z.re` rather than `z.1.1`.
- You seem to be applying `Complex.abs` to a real number. This is OK since it gets silently coerced to a complex again, but then that adds complication to later calculations. Doesn't it make life easier to use either `Real.abs` or `Real.norm` here?
- You're inside the `UpperHalfPlane` namespace so the name of the def expands to `UpperHalfPlane.upperHalfPlaneSlice` which is a bit repetitious. Maybe `verticalStrip` is better?
- `rcases` and `obtain` are pretty much synonymous, but I think it's better style to use `rcases` when there's an actual case-split going on, and `obtain` when you're just unpacking data
- Most seriously: you are making your life hugely more difficult than it needs to be by using the invariant metric on the upper half-plane. That metric is important since it's invariant under Moebius transformations, but the formulae describing it are complicated, and you don't need the Moebius invariance here ‚Äì indeed you don't need a metric at all, just a topology, and the topology is the one induced by the inclusion into  `‚ÑÇ`. So you can massively slash the length of this proof by not mentioning the metric at all, and using the approach you already use to get `b` via `isMinOn` to get the bound on the real part as well.

Here's my best attempt at golfing it, which reduces the proof from 22 lines to 6:

```suggestion
section slices

/-- The vertical strip of width A and height B. -/
def upperHalfPlaneSlice (A B : ‚Ñù) := {z : ‚Ñç | |z.re| ‚â§ A ‚àß B ‚â§ z.im}

theorem slice_mem_iff (A B : ‚Ñù) (z : ‚Ñç) : z ‚àà upperHalfPlaneSlice A B ‚Üî |z.re| ‚â§ A ‚àß B ‚â§ z.im := 
  Iff.rfl

lemma subset_slice_of_isCompact {K : Set ‚Ñç} (hK : IsCompact K) :
    ‚àÉ A B : ‚Ñù, 0 < B ‚àß K ‚äÜ upperHalfPlaneSlice A B := by
  rcases K.eq_empty_or_nonempty with rfl | hne 
  ¬∑ exact ‚ü®1, 1, Real.zero_lt_one, empty_subset _‚ü©
  obtain ‚ü®u, _, hu‚ü© := hK.exists_isMinOn hne continuous_im.continuousOn
  obtain ‚ü®v, _, hv‚ü© := hK.exists_isMaxOn hne (_root_.continuous_abs.comp continuous_re).continuousOn
  exact ‚ü®|re v|, im u, u.im_pos, fun k hk ‚Ü¶ ‚ü®isMaxOn_iff.mp hv _ hk, isMinOn_iff.mp hu _ hk‚ü©‚ü©

end slices
```

Several points here:

- `nlinarith` is extremely slow, and it is overkill to use it for this very simple inequality. 
- I think it's a lot simpler to write `foo ^ 2` rather than `foo * foo` and then rewrite backwards the output of `normSq_apply`.
- Using `rcases` saves you writing all the explicit binders `z : ‚ÑÇ` everywhere.
- `im_ofReal_mul` and `re_ofReal_mul` are handy shortcuts.
- `simp at *` seems a bit of a scattergun approach, why not check where you really want to simp?
- In the statement, `Complex.abs` can only take a `‚ÑÇ` argument, so you don't need the type annotation `(z : ‚ÑÇ)` ‚Äì Lean can see for itself that `z` needs to be coerced.

```suggestion
lemma auxbound1 (z : ‚Ñç) {Œ¥ : ‚Ñù} (Œµ : ‚Ñù) (hŒ¥ : 1 ‚â§ Œ¥ ^ 2) : r z ‚â§ Complex.abs (Œ¥ * z + Œµ) := by
  rcases z with ‚ü®z, hz‚ü©
  have H1 : z.im ‚â§ ‚àö((Œ¥ * z.re + Œµ) ^ 2 + (Œ¥ * z).im ^ 2) := by
    rw [Real.le_sqrt' hz, im_ofReal_mul, mul_pow]
    exact (le_mul_of_one_le_left (sq_nonneg _) hŒ¥).trans <| le_add_of_nonneg_left (sq_nonneg _)
  simpa only [r, abs_apply, normSq_apply, add_re, re_ofReal_mul, coe_re, ‚Üê pow_two, add_im, mul_im,
    coe_im, ofReal_im, zero_mul, add_zero, min_le_iff] using Or.inl H1
```

Similar comments as the previous proof.
```suggestion
lemma auxbound2 (z : ‚Ñç) (Œ¥ : ‚Ñù) {Œµ : ‚Ñù} (hŒµ : 1 ‚â§ Œµ ^ 2) : r z ‚â§ Complex.abs (Œ¥ * z + Œµ) := by
  have H1 : ‚àö(r1 z) ‚â§ ‚àö((Œ¥ * z.re + Œµ) ^ 2 + (Œ¥ * z.im) ^ 2) :=
    (Real.sqrt_le_sqrt_iff (by positivity)).mpr (r1_aux_bound _ _ hŒµ)
  simpa only [r, abs_apply, normSq_apply, add_re, re_ofReal_mul, coe_re, ofReal_re, ‚Üê pow_two,
    add_im, im_ofReal_mul, coe_im, ofReal_im, add_zero, min_le_iff] using Or.inr H1
```

One line longer, but twice as fast:
```suggestion
lemma left_ne_zero_of_max_eq {x : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ñ§} (hx : x ‚â† 0)
    (h : max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs = (x 0).natAbs) : x 0 ‚â† 0 := by
  contrapose! hx
  rw [hx, Int.natAbs_zero, max_eq_left_iff, Nat.le_zero, Int.natAbs_eq_zero] at h
  ext1 j
  fin_cases j <;> assumption
```
(If you prefer the shorter proof I won't insist; but please don't use `x` for the name of the variable introduced by `ext`, since `x` is already the name of the function, so you're trying to reason about the function `x` evaluated at `x`!)

This proof is both faster and shorter:
```suggestion
lemma right_ne_zero_of_max_eq {x : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ñ§} (hx : x ‚â† 0)
    (h : (max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs) = (x 1).natAbs) : x 1 ‚â† 0 := by
  contrapose! hx
  rw [hx, Int.natAbs_zero, max_eq_right_iff, Nat.le_zero, Int.natAbs_eq_zero] at h
  ext1 j
  fin_cases j <;> assumption
```

alternative suggestion (not much difference to the original really):
```suggestion
lemma div_max_sq_ge_one (x : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ñ§) (hx : x ‚â† 0) :
    (1 : ‚Ñù) ‚â§ (x 0 / (max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs)) ^ 2 ‚à®
      (1 : ‚Ñù) ‚â§ (x 1 / (max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs)) ^ 2 := by
  rcases max_choice (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs with H1 | H2
  ¬∑ simp only [H1, Int.cast_natAbs, Int.cast_abs, div_pow, _root_.sq_abs, ne_eq,
      OfNat.ofNat_ne_zero, not_false_eq_true, pow_eq_zero_iff, Int.cast_eq_zero,
      left_ne_zero_of_max_eq hx H1, div_self, le_refl, true_or]
  ¬∑ simp only [H2, Int.cast_natAbs, Int.cast_abs, div_pow, _root_.sq_abs, ne_eq,
      OfNat.ofNat_ne_zero, not_false_eq_true, pow_eq_zero_iff, Int.cast_eq_zero,
      right_ne_zero_of_max_eq hx H2, div_self, le_refl, or_true]
```
The original one is marginally faster, so I'll keep it (modulo the name changes needed).

- There's no need to handle the case `k = 0` separately; the general-case proof works fine for `k = 0` also.
- Please don't use type annotations like `(x 0 : ‚ÑÇ)` unnecessarily. Lean is _very_ good at guessing types for itself, and you'll hurt its feelings if you treat it as if it's stupid. :-). I have cultivated a habit that before PR'ing any code, I go through every type annotation and try deleting it to see if the code still works.
- You have an absolute epidemic of redundant brackets (here and in many other places in the code).
- You seem to be jumping through hoops in order to use your lemma `eq_zero_iff_eq_zero_of_mem_box`, in a situation where it's easier just to prove the result directly.
- The `field_simp` call takes about 0.7 sec on my machine, which is an eternity given how fast modern computers are! The overhead of firing up `field_simp` is so great that it's absolutely not worth using it for simple little goals like this one which can be `rw`'ed in a few steps by hand.
- I removed many type annotations from `h11`. The new expression elaborates slightly differently (replacing a two-step cast  `‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñù ‚Üí ‚ÑÇ` with `‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚ÑÇ`), but the difference is a gain, not a loss, as it simplifies arguments further down.
```suggestion
lemma rpow_bound {k : ‚Ñù} (hk : 0 ‚â§ k) (z : ‚Ñç) (x : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ñ§) (hx : x ‚â† 0) :
    (r z) ^ k * (max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs) ^ k ‚â§ Complex.abs (x 0 * z + x 1) ^ k := by
  rw [‚Üê Real.mul_rpow (r_pos _).le (Nat.cast_nonneg _)]
  refine Real.rpow_le_rpow (mul_nonneg (r_pos _).le (Nat.cast_nonneg _)) ?_ hk
  let n := max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs
  have hn0 : n ‚â† 0 := by
    contrapose! hx
    rw [Nat.max_eq_zero_iff, Int.natAbs_eq_zero, Int.natAbs_eq_zero] at hx
    exact funext fun j ‚Ü¶ by fin_cases j <;> tauto
  have h11 : x 0 * (z : ‚ÑÇ) + x 1 = (x 0 / n * z + x 1 / n) * n := by
    push_cast
    rw [div_mul_eq_mul_div, ‚Üê add_div, div_mul_cancel‚ÇÄ _ (Nat.cast_ne_zero.mpr hn0)]
  rw [Nat.cast_max, h11, map_mul, abs_natCast]
  gcongr
  ¬∑ rcases div_max_sq_ge_one x hx with H1 | H2
    ¬∑ simpa only [Fin.isValue, ofReal_div, ofReal_intCast, n] using auxbound1 z (x 1 / n) H1
    ¬∑ simpa only [Fin.isValue, ofReal_div, ofReal_intCast, n] using auxbound2 z (x 0 / n) H2
  ¬∑ norm_cast
```

Here you prove an inequality with `k`-th powers; but since it is actually use the `-k`-th powers that you use later, you have to invoke `Real.rpow_neg` three times over and prove a positivity hypothesis each time. Why not just forget `k` in this lemma and prove `r z * max (x 0).natAbs (x 1).natAbs ‚â§ Complex.abs (x 0 * z + x 1)` (it will need a new name of course)?
see comment below.

Then this whole proof shortens to
```suggestion
  by_cases hn : n = 0
  ¬∑ simp only [hn, box_zero, Finset.mem_singleton, Prod.mk_eq_zero] at hx
    rw [hx.1, hx.2, hn, ‚Üê Real.mul_rpow (r_pos z).le (Nat.cast_nonneg 0)]
    simp only [Int.cast_zero, zero_mul, add_zero, map_zero, CharP.cast_eq_zero, mul_zero, le_refl]
  ¬∑ simp only [Fin.isValue, Pi.zero_apply, Int.mem_box, Int.natAbs_zero, max_self] at hx
    have hx2 : x ‚â† 0 := by
      contrapose! hn
      simpa only [hn, Fin.isValue, Pi.zero_apply, Int.natAbs_zero, max_self] using hx.symm
    rw [‚Üê Real.mul_rpow (r_pos _).le (Nat.cast_nonneg _)]
    exact Real.rpow_le_rpow_of_nonpos (mul_pos (r_pos _) (by positivity)) (hx ‚ñ∏ r_mul_max_le z hx2) 
      (neg_nonpos.mpr hk)
```
oh very nice, I've done this this and used the `r_mul_max_le` name you suggest in your proof :)

```suggestion
    (a : Fin 2 ‚Üí ZMod N) : TendstoLocallyUniformlyOn (fun (s : Finset (gammaSet N a)) ‚Ü¶
      ‚Üë‚Çï(fun (z : ‚Ñç) ‚Ü¶ ‚àë x in s, eisSummand k x z)) (‚Üë‚Çï(eisensteinSeries_SIF a k).toFun)
```
